<subSubSection id="029DC8B73E216919322CD585FD80FA04" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="4A389B3C3E216919322CD585FD80FA04" blockId="17.[113,1089,1438,1526]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
<emphasis id="78F3472E3E216919322CD585FF67FA44" bold="true" box="[113,243,1438,1462]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Comments.</emphasis>
The specimen is damaged and lacks terminalia. It resembles 
<taxonomicName id="8D87E0BF3E2169193128D5BBFF3DFA24" authority="Flor, 1861" authorityName="Flor" authorityYear="1861" class="Insecta" family="Triozidae" genus="Trioza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="alacris">
<emphasis id="78F3472E3E2169193128D5BBFB9DFA45" box="[885,1033,1440,1463]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Trioza alacris</emphasis>
Flor, 1861
</taxonomicName>
, in general aspect but differs in the relatively shorter and broader forewings. More material is needed for its identification.
</paragraph>
